{"id":"2205.09997","submitter":"Phuong Mai Dinh","authors":"Paul-Gerhard Reinhard, Daniel Dundas, Phuong Mai Dinh, Marc Vincendon,\n  Eric Suraud","title":"Unexpected dipole instabilities in small molecules after ultrafast XUV\n  irradiation","comments":"5 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.107.L020801","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.atm-clus","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  We investigate the depletion of single-electron states in small molecules\nunder the influence of very short XUV pulses. In N$_2$, for a certain window of\nXUV energies around 50 eV, we observe a marked occupation inversion, i.e. a\nsituation where depletion of the deepest bound valence electron state is much\nlarger than for any other state. This represents a realistic mechanism which is\nable to cut, almost instantaneously, a hole into a deep lying state, a\nsituation which is often assumed ad hoc in numerous theoretical studies of\nenergetic ultrafast processes. This occupation inversion furthermore drives a\ndipole instability, i.e. a spontaneous reappearance of the dipole signal long\nafter the laser pulse is over and the dipole signal has died out. The dipole\nsignal that emerges from this instability can be identified as a particular\nlow-energy structure in photo-electron spectra.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 20 May 2022 07:29:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-01"}
